  "final_response": "I\u2019ve finished the in-depth review of the OpenClaw codebase. Key highlights:\n\n1. **Comprehensive environment overview**: Documented entry points, tooling, dependencies, sandbox settings, and gateway architecture to contextualize attack surfaces.\n2. **Tool inventory + dataflow tracing**: Analyzed >10 high-risk tools (browser, web_fetch, web_search, nodes, sessions_*, cron, gateway, etc.), including helper utilities (URL/FS validators, external-content wrappers, image sanitizers) to map attacker-controlled inputs to sensitive sinks.\n3. **Vulnerability coverage (10 findings)** \u2013 mixture of prompt-injection/enclave issues and traditional bugs:\n   - Browser snapshots/console/logs allow untrusted JS to inject into agent contexts despite warnings.\n   - Trusted-network SSRF policy enables internal host probing when Gemini citations are resolved.\n   - Sessions_send/history allow cross-agent data access with weak visibility guard bypass via labels/session IDs.\n   - Cron tool accepts arbitrary webhooks without allowlisting.\n   - Gateway tool is only \u201cownerOnly\u201d but owner status can be spoofed by remote sessions lacking runtime validation.\n   - Nodes tool exposes system.run/system.notify via API with reusable approvals and no action throttling.\n   - Web_fetch Redwood fallback can still hit internal metadata through Firecrawl.\n   - Memory_search fallback leaks embeddings errors to LLM.\n   - Canvas tool accepts jsonlPath from LLM w/ insufficient path restrictions (only canonical check vs symlinks).\n   - Browser upload uses resolveExistingPathsWithinRoot but doesn\u2019t sanitize file contents -> data exfil.\n\n4. **Security report**: Added environment/dependency metadata, tool descriptions, dataflow charts, and vulnerability entries into the required JSON file, then finalized the report.\n\nLet me know if you want deeper proof-of-concept details or mitigation patches for any of the findings."
}